            <fr:route>sga1-i.6.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group › Étale morphisms › Application to étale extensions of complete local rings"><fr:link type="local" href="sga1-i.xml" addr="sga1-i" title="SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group › Étale morphisms"><fr:link type="local" href="sga1.xml" addr="sga1" title="SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group">SGA 1: Étale covers and the fundamental group</fr:link> › Étale morphisms</fr:link> › Application to étale extensions of complete local rings</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Section</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>I.6</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>sga1-i</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>This section is a particular case of the results on formal preschemes, which should appear in the multiplodoque.
  Nevertheless, here we get away without much difficulty, i.e. without the explicit local determination of the étale morphisms in [sga1-i.7 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>] (using the Main Theorem).
  This is perhaps sufficient reason to keep this current section (even in the multiplodoque) where it is.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>530</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.6.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.6.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.6.1</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.6</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> be a complete local ring (Noetherian, of course), with residue field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>.
    For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R(B)=B\otimes _Ak]]></fr:tex> be thought of as a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-algebra;
    this depends functorially on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.
    Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> defines an <fr:em>equivalence</fr:em> between the category of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-algebras that are <fr:em>finite and étale over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex></fr:em> and the category of algebras that are <fr:em>finite rank and separable over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex></fr:em>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Firstly, the functor in question is fully faithful, as follows from the more general fact:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>531</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">sga1-i.6.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>sga1-i.6.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>I.6.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>sga1-i.6</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B']]></fr:tex> be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>-algebras that are finite over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is étale over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then the canonical map
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {Hom}_{A\mathsf {-alg}}(B,B')       \to  \operatorname {Hom}_{k\mathsf {-alg}}(R(B),R(B'))     ]]></fr:tex>
    is bijective.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>511</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#253</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-253.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>sga1-i.6.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We can reduce to the case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is Artinian (by replacing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/\frak {m}^n]]></fr:tex>), and then this is a particular case of <fr:ref addr="sga1-i.5.5" href="sga1-i.5.5.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="I.5.5" />.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>It remains to prove that, for every finite and separable <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> algebra (or we can simply say "étale", for brevity) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>, there exists some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> étale over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R(B)]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex>.
  We can suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> is a separable extension of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>, and, as such, it admits a generator <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>, i.e. it is isomorphic to an algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k[t]/Fk[t]]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F\in  k[t]]]></fr:tex> is a monic polynomial.
  We can lift <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> to a monic polynomial <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_1]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A[t]]]></fr:tex>, and we take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B=A[t]/F_1A[t]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
